The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 06, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 5: Avaya Mauritius Ltd and associates are making an open offer to acquire a 25.1 per cent stake in Tata Telecom from the Tata group. Avaya will buy the 28.46-lakh shares of Rs 10 each for Rs 220 per share. The offer would open on May 13 and close on June 11, DSP Merill Lynch, lead manager to the offer, informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today. The offer by Avaya Mauritius Ltd, along with Avaya Inc and Avaya International Ltd, is not conditional to any minimum level of acceptance by the shareholders, it said.																								 Mumbai, April 5: The Reserve Bank of India today directed banks to accept coins of all denominations tendered at their branches either for exchange or deposit in accounts. Despite requesting banks to instruct branches to accept coins of all denominations from any member of the public without any restriction, we still continue to receive complaints about non-acceptance of coins, the RBI said.																								 Calcutta, April 5: The debt recovery tribunal has appointed a receiver for Haldia Petrochemicals Ltd following the companys failure to pay around Rs 16 crore as interest on debentures issued to Unit Trust of India by it.																								 New Delhi, April 5: The governments total tax collection fell marginally short of the revised estimates of Rs 2,44,600 crore during 2003-04. The finance ministry, however, was confident of achieving the target, expecting some more revenue that is in the pipeline. 																								 Chennai, April 5: The Cellular Operators Association of India (COAI) is crying fowl over Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltds decision to cut long-distance call-rates by 25 per cent. It has termed the decision as anti-competitive.																								 New Delhi, April 5: The country needs to open up its markets if it wants America to understand its concerns on the business process outsourcing backlash in that country, said Carla Hill, former US trade representative.																								 Mumbai, April 5: D-Link India Ltd has acquired a 10 per cent stake in Mercury Link Systems Ltd for Rs 35 lakh.
